title: For Sale/Trade:  1855-1866 Vintage Ward & Sons Coach Gun
postcontent: I'm looking to get rid of my vintage Ward & Son's coach gun (properly called a "guard gun" in the UK). Original EVERYTING. We recently found it in my grandfathers safe and did some research on it. Despite the appearance, this is a legal-length shotgun in the USA - Barrels measure in at 18.5" and overall is 34". Ward & Son's was a Birmingham gunmaker (William Ward) between the warly 1800's until just up to prior to the start of WWII. This particular piece is a "Bar-action hammer gun" with a "Fine London Twist" damascus barrel, and is thought to be an authentic "coach gun" or "guard gun". I have photos of all the authentic Birmingham proof marks to verify authenticity, and many more phtos of the gun. While more common in the early western US, the "Coach gun" or "Guard gun" as it is referred to in the UK is a shotgun with a barrel length of around 18 inches, usually with a partial pistol grip or horned stock, designed specifically for concealment by law enforcement. While it is thought that Ward & Son's did indeed make a few of these with original short barrels, none of the Birmingham gunmakers of the time specifically documented this, nor did a proof specific to barrel length exist yet. Because of this, while I am saying this is "original everything" I am only asking for the "wall hanger" value, as I have no proof that the barrels weren't modified at a later time. YES this gun is over 150 years old, and YES it still fires. That said, I will be removing the firing pins and packaging them separately for whomever purchases them. You will only reassemble and fire this with the understanding that modern shotgun shells fired through a gun like this can MAKE THE BARREL EXPLODE. IF YOU INTEND TO PURCHASE/TRADE THIS TO FIRE IT, I AM NOT RESPONSIBLE FOR INJURY/DAMAGE/DEATH OR AYTHING ELSE. DAMASCUS BARRELS ARE PROOFED ONLY FOR BLACK POWDER, NOT SMOKELESS, AND SHOULD ONLY ONLY ONLY ONLY ONLY BE FIRED BY/UNDER SUPERVISION OF SOMEONE FAMILIAR WITH VINTAGE FIREARM SAFETY!That said, I'm looking to sell or trade this for something I can safely hunt with. I'm interested in decent shotguns for turkey season, or a rifle of a caliber I can at least bag a deer with.
